      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The process considered is amination of carbon disulfide.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">This continuous, pressure-free process is carried out in two steps. In the first step CS2 and ammonia gas are reacted in the presence of water over activated charcoal at ca. 50 °C in an in-terface reactor to give ammonium dithiocarbamate. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">The latter is decomposed in the second step at 95 – 100 °C on activated charcoal. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">If the NH3 and CS2 used are of high purity, the 35 – 45 % ammonium thiocyanate solution formed can be marketed after concentration without further purification. The crystals, which are produced by vacuum evaporation and centrifugation, are of higher purity. In this process, apart from H2S and excess CS2, no other waste substances are formed. After CS2 and H2S have been separated, the former can be recycled and the latter can be used, for example, for sulfur production in the Claus process. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Claus process:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">2H2S + O2 → 2S + 2H2O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11">From sulfur carbon disulfide is produced. The</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="12"> CS2 production reaction is:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="13"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="14"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="15">CH4 + 4 S → CS2 + 2 H2S</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="16"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="17"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="18">There is also a one-step variant of this process in which the reaction of NH3 with CS2 and decomposition take place at ca. 115 °C and 5 bar.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="19">The whole chemical equation with included desulfurizing and CS2-production from the recovered sulfur is:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="20"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="21"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="22">CS2 + 4 NH3 + 2 O2 + CH4→ 2NH4SCN + 4H2O</text>
          <imageUrl index="23">https://db3.ecoinvent.org/images/19b8420b-ffd1-403f-85d6-b0cc3a3bd748</imageUrl>
          <imageUrl index="24">https://db3.ecoinvent.org/images/0e2080a3-88d4-4113-bff6-29ab13fc065b</imageUrl>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="25">Hoek, Theo van: Thiocyanates, Inorganic. In: Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Seventh Edition, 2004 Electronic Release (ed. Fiedler E., Grossmann G., Kersebohm D., Weiss G. and Witte C.). 7 th Electronic Release Edition. Wiley InterScience, New York, Online-Version under: http://www.mrw.interscience.wiley.com/emrw/9783527306732/home</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2000-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Time of publications</text>
