    </activityDescription>
    <flowData>
      <intermediateExchange id="54c6cf6e-58e4-51e8-ad24-cdd6859e75b8" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" casNumber="1762-95-4" amount="1.0" intermediateExchangeId="4d8591e3-c13b-4364-8fd9-c48c3996588a" productionVolumeAmount="1.0">
        <name xml:lang="en">ammonium thiocyanate</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">EcoSpold01Location=GLO
Ammonium thiocyanate is a white, hygroscopic salt which forms stable monoclinic crystals below 90 - 92 °C. At higher temperatures it is converted to the rhombic form.
Ammonium thiocyanate is readily soluble in many polar solvents, such as ethanol and acetone.

Most of the ammonium thiocyanate is produced as an intermediate in the production of other inorganic thiocyanates. It is also used as the starting material for compounds such as aminothiazoles.
Large quantities of ammonium thiocyanate are used in agriculture. It is used to combat worms in cattle and, as a mixture with aminotriazole, reinforces the activity of the latter as a broad-spectrum herbicide. Ammonium thiocyanate is also used as a raw material or the production of other herbicides, such as diallates, triallates and tricyclazoles. It is also used as a raw material for fungicides, such as methyl isothiocyanate.
Ammonium thiocyanate is extensively used in photography as an accelerator with sodium thiosulfate in fixing baths, where it removes undeveloped silver (Ag+). Addition of ammonium thiocyanate to electrolytic cells in the production of ammonium peroxodisulfate, (NH4)2S2O8 considerably increases the yield.

Ammonium thiocyanate is used as a solvent for cellulose, which can also be spun. In the textile industry ammonium thiocyanate is widely used to improve desired properties.

In the steel industry ammonium thiocyanate is used for coating and as a corrosion inhibitor against acidic gases. It is used as an additive for silver and tin plating baths and for etching aluminum.

Because of the neutron-absorbing properties of hafnium, only hafnium-free zirconium can be used in nuclear technology. Following their extraction, Zr and Hf are dissolved in aqueous ammonium thiocyanate so that the Hf(SCN)4 complex can subsequently be extracted with an organic solvent.

Ammonium thiocyanate can also be used as a component for energy storage in combination with heat pumps, in vulcanization, for the production of fire-extinguishing agents, and in absorbents for ammonia or steam.</comment>
